photos.Observation Details: Continuing bird first found by Jerry Ting. Large shorebird very similar to the many nearby Marbled Godwits, but drabber, with much less orange color, plain white belly, and mostly unpatterned back. Smaller than nearby Marbled Godwits and lacking orange tones (except on the front of the face, maybe a stain from the mud?). White supercilium, streaked as opposed to barred upperparts, black and white striped tail and rump, mostly white underparts with black streaking on the flanks. Spent most of the time tucked in but occasionally looked around or preened.

photos.Media notes: Encounter 3
photos.Observation Details: Dull bird in fennel in north/nw part of park. Still not certain on species but here are my thoughts based on the distinguishing characteristics listed by Kaufman in Field Guide to Advanced Birding. Crown: Brown with streaking and weak median stripe seems inconclusive for either Brewer's or Clay-colored but probably leaning Brewer's. Supercilium: Grayish, supporting Brewer's, but obviously distinct from crown and eye line, supporting Clay-colored. Doesn't appear to be invaded by streaking but edges don't appear to be very neat, so probably more leaning Brewer's. Malar: Dark lateral throat stripe with white submoustachial stripe point towards Clay-colored, maybe the strongest feature leaning in that direction. Neck and nape: Appears clean gray and contrasting with back crown color, supporting Clay-colored. However, in photos by other birders it looks like there is streaking on the back of the nape which points to Brewer's. Breast color: Appears grayish with no buffy tones, supporting Brewer's. Ear coverts: Strongly bordered not ruling out either species.  I think there was just one bird, but there might have been two. I encountered the bird(s) three times. Description in images indicate which encounter they are from.

Initially seen near the southeast entrance to the meadow, around 37.866724, -122.306349. Flushed when a jogger came by and not found again for a couple of hours, this time near information sign by the big willow patch around 37.867571, -122.306448. It then flew west but reemerged along the other path from the SE entrance, around 37.866834, -122.306984. It then stayed in the same general area, mostly sticking to the fences and weeds immediately next to them.  Very small, bright warbler. Blue grayish on top, white with a warm wash below. Noticeable light fuzzy eye ring. No wing bars. Rusty rump was difficult to see in the field but comes through in photos. The bird didn't seem very skulky. Often by itself but occasionally found with sparrows or Bushtits. Seemed to associate closely with Field Wormweed which can be seen in all of my photos.
